Machine learning on Titanic disaster

Author: Paul Bustios

Table of contents

  1. Introduction
  2. Objective
  3. Requirements
  4. Getting the data
  5. Analyzing the data
  6. Selecting a model
  7. Testing the model
  8. Conclusion

1. Introduction

The sinking of the RMS Titanic is one of the most infamous shipwrecks in history. On April 15, 1912, during her maiden voyage, the Titanic sank after colliding with an iceberg, killing 1502 out of 2224 passengers and crew. This tragedy shocked the international community and led to better safety regulations for ships. One of the reasons that the shipwreck led to such loss of life was that there were not enough lifeboats for the passengers and crew. Although there was some element of luck involved in surviving the sinking, some groups of people were more likely to survive than others, such as women, children, and the upper-class. – From: Kaggle

RMS Titanic. Image source: Wikipedia

2. Objective

This notebook is intended to show the common steps present in a machine learning problem. For that, we are going to setup a try to predict if a person had survived to the sinking based on the information contained in the Titanic dataset.

3. Requirements

To be able to execute the code in this notebook, it is necessary to have installed Python 3.5 and the following libraries:

  • Matplotlib = 1.5.1
  • Pandas = 0.18.0
  • Scikit-learn = 0.17.1
  • Seaborn = 0.7.0

If you already have installed other versions and want to maintain them and your system stability or just want to avoid problems managing dependencies, you can use Miniconda, a reduced version of Anaconda Python distribution, with Python 3.5. Once installed Miniconda, you can install the libraries using the command:

conda install pandas scikit-learn seaborn

This command will install the latest versions of these libraries and will keep them along with Python 3.5 in a virtual environment completely independent of system libraries.

4. Getting the data

First, we have to download the Titanic dataset from http://biostat.mc.vanderbilt.edu/DataSets, specifically the titanic3.csv file. This dataset contains information of 1309 passengers arranged in 14 variables. You can find more information about this dataset here.

paragraphs.text:
%python
import pandas as pd

# Connect to S3 data source
bucket = z.getDatasource("Titanic_Data")

# Connect to Titanic csv file from the desired S3 bucket
data = bucket.Object("titanic3.csv")

data.download_file("./titanic3.csv" )

5. Analyzing the data

The objective of this step is to know the data and improve our understanding of the problem. Let's load the data and take a look at it using Pandas. Each row represents a passenger on the Titanic and each column contains some information about them. The columns are:

  1. pclass: the class the passenger was in (1 = first class, 2 = second class, 3 = third class).
  2. survived: whether the passenger survived (0 = no, 1 = yes). We will predict this value.
  3. name: the name of the passenger.
  4. sex: the gender of the passenger (male, female).
  5. age: the age of the passenger. It can be fractional if the age is less than one or is estimated.
  6. sibsp: the number of siblings and spouses the passenger had on board.
  7. parch: the number of parents and children the passenger had on board.
  8. ticket: the ticket number of the passenger.
  9. fare: how much the passenger paid for the ticker.
  10. cabin: which cabin the passenger was in.
  11. embarked: where the passenger boarded the Titanic (C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton).
  12. boat: for survivors, the lifeboat identifier from which they were known to be rescued.
  13. body: for victims, the body identification number.
  14. home.dest: passenger's home/destination.

Now, we are going to divide the data into train and test subsets. For that we are going to use scikit-learn. Scikit-learn is a Python module for machine learning with many other utilities to deal with common tasks in machine learning.

We have set random_state = 1 in train_test_split function to guarantee that the split will be always the same for reproducible results.

    random_state=1,
    stratify=titanic["survived"])

print("Test set size: %d" % X_test.shape[0])

6. Selecting a model

Now that all our data is numeric, we are ready to select and apply a machine learning model to predict the survivors. There are many models, so what should we choose? Since our problem consist in predicting a value which can be zero or one, we are going to choose a linear model, specifically a Logistic Regression model. But, why a logistic regression model? We choose it for two reasons:

  • Before to try a sofisticated model, we have to start with the simplest. A simple model is not always a bad model.
  • Logistic regression predicts categorical values, and that's what we want.

In addition to logistic regression, we are going to use a Random Forest, a more complex model, and compare the results of both classifiers.

8. Conclusion

By history, we know that women had priority to be saved and, as a matter of fact, this feature is the most important in both the logistic regression and the random forest. Another important feature is the age, in the case of logistic regression, it is not as important as in the random forest. That's probably why random forest performed better than logistic regression, but not by much. So, we can conclude that a simple model is not always a bad model.
